Part I - Communicate Ford GoBike System Data Findings¶

by Augustine Omoregbee¶

Introduction¶

The Ford GoBike System dateset contains information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area.

Specific information being provided in the dataset include bike ID, user type, member gender, member birth year, start station ID and coordinates, end station ID and coordinates, trip start time, trip end time and trip duration.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset contains records for 183412 bike rides that happened February, 2019 in San Francisco Bay area.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

My main features of interest are in how user characteristics such as age, gender and purpose in the Ford GoBike sytem data, influence bike usage in the forms of trip duration, start time, start day, distance and bike sharing. It is my assumption that trip duration varies directly as the distance between start and end stations.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

  • duration_sec
  • start_time
  • start_station_name
  • start_station_latitude
  • start_station_longitude
  • end_station_name
  • end_station_latitude
  • end_station_longitude
  • member_birth_year
  • member_gender

Dataset Quality Issues¶

  • Presence of rows with missing values.
  • Some columns are not needed.
  • Dataset contains ages which are considered not ideal for bike users.
  • The start_station_id, end_station_id and bike_id variables should be of string data types.
  • The start_time and end_time variables should be of datetime data types.
  • The user_type and member_gender variables should be of category data types.

def to_str(df, variables):
    """
    This function converts a given variable to a string data type.
    
    Parameters:
        df: DataFrame of interest
        variable (String): Variable to be converted
    """
    for variable in variables:
        df[variable] = df[variable].astype(str)
    return df

def to_timestamp(df, variables):
    """
    This function converts a given variable to a datetime data type.
    
    Parameters:
        df: DataFrame of interest
        variable (String): Variable to be converted
    """
    for variable in variables:
        df[variable] = pd.to_datetime(df[variable])
    return df

def to_category(df, variables):
    """
    This function converts a given variable to a category data type.
    
    Parameters:
        df: DataFrame of interest
        variable (String): Variable to be converted
    """
    for variable in variables:
        df[variable] = df[variable].astype('category')
    return df

Create a new column representing the distance between start and end stations.

In [88]:
# code copied form "Getting distance between two points based on latitude/longitude" on stackoverflow
# https://stackoverflow.com/questions/19412462/getting-distance-between-two-points-based-on-latitude-longitude
from math import sin, cos, sqrt, atan2, radians

def distance (lat1, lon1, lat2, lon2):
    # multiply R, earth's radius (km), by 0.621 to convert it to miles
    R = 6373.0 * 0.621
    
    lat1 = radians(lat1)
    lon1 = radians(lon1)
    lat2 = radians(lat2)
    lon2 = radians(lon2)

    dlon = lon2 - lon1
    dlat = lat2 - lat1

    a = sin(dlat / 2)**2 + cos(lat1) * cos(lat2) * sin(dlon / 2)**2
    c = 2 * atan2(sqrt(a), sqrt(1 - a))

    d = R * c
    return d
In [89]:
# create a column for the distance covered
df_clean['distance_miles'] = (df_clean.apply(lambda x: distance(x['start_station_latitude'], x['start_station_longitude'], 
                                             x['end_station_latitude'], x['end_station_longitude']),axis=1)).round(3)

def bar_plot(df, var_name, x_label, title):
    """
    This function makes a bar plot of a specified variable.
    
    Parameters:
        df: DataFrame of interest
        var_name (string): Name of variable to be plotted
        x_label (string): horizontal axis label
        title (string): plot title.   
    """
    # order the unique values by count
    var_count = df[var_name].value_counts()[:25]
    
    # make a bar plot of the variable
    sb.countplot(data = df, y = var_name, order = var_count.index, color = base_color)
    # add x label
    plt.xlabel(x_label, weight = 'bold')
    # override the default y label
    plt.ylabel(None)
    # add title and format it
    plt.title(title, size = 14, weight = 'bold')

def bar_plot(df, var_count, var_name, x_label, y_label, title, order = None):
    """
    This function makes a bar plot of a specified variable.
    
    Parameters:
        df: DataFrame of interest
        var_count (String): Variable count
        order (String): Variable order
        var_name (string): Variable to be plotted
        x_label (string): horizontal axis label
        y_label (string): vertical axis label.
        title (string): plot title.  
    """
    # order the unique values by count
    var_count = df[var_name].value_counts()

    # adjust figure size
    plt.figure(figsize = [11, 5])
    # set base color
    base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    # make a bar plot of the variable
    sb.countplot(data = df, x = var_name, color = base_color, order = order)
    # add x label and format it
    plt.xlabel(x_label, size = 12, weight = 'bold')
    # add y label and format it
    plt.ylabel(y_label, size = 12, weight = 'bold')
    # add title and format it 
    plt.title(title, size = 14, weight = 'bold');

def bi_plot(plot_type, df, x_data, y_data, order = None):
    """
    This function makes a either a violin or box plot between to specified variables.
    
    Parameters:
        df: DataFrame of interest
        plot_type: Plot type, either violin plot (sb.violinplot) or box plot (sb.boxplot)
        x_data (string): Variable on the x_axis.
        y_data (string): Variable on the y_axis.
        
    """
    plot_type(data = df, x = x_data, y = y_data, color = sb.color_palette()[0], order = order)
    # tidy up labels after plotting
    x_data = x_data.replace('_', ' ') # replace underscore symbol with space
    y_data = y_data.replace('_', ' ') # replace underscore symbol with space
    # add x label and format it
    plt.xlabel(x_data.title(), size = 12, weight = 'bold')
    # add y label and format it
    plt.ylabel(y_data.title(), size = 12, weight = 'bold')
    # add title and format it
    plt.title(f'Distribution of {y_data} by {x_data}'.title(), size = 14, weight = 'bold')

def map_plot(df, x_data, y_data, z_data, xs = 5, ys = 5, col_order = None):
    """
    This function makes a heatmap plot of the specified variables for a given DataFrame.
    
    Parameters:
        df: DataFrame of interest
        x_data (string): Numerical variable on the x_axis
        y_data (string): Numerical variable on the y_axis
        z_data (string): Categorical variable
        xs and ys = horizontal and vertical intervals respectively
        
    """
    # set bins
    xbin = np.arange((df[x_data].min() // xs) * xs, df[x_data].max() +xs, xs)
    ybin = np.arange(0, df[y_data].max() +ys, ys)
    
    # make the plot
    g = sb.FacetGrid(data = df, col = z_data, height = xs, col_order = col_order)
    g.map(plt.hist2d, x_data, y_data, cmin = 0.1, cmap = 'viridis_r', bins = [xbin, ybin])
    plt.colorbar()
    # set plot size
    g.fig.set_size_inches(14, 5);
